{"title_page": "Esher railway station", "text_new": "{{redirect|Esher station|the request stop in Ontario|Esher station (Ontario)}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name         = Esher\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = Esher station westbound look east2.JPG\n| manager      = [[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]]\n| locale       = [[Esher]]\n| borough      = [[Borough of Elmbridge|Elmbridge]]\n| start        = 21 May 1838\n| platforms    = 4 (2 in use)\n<!-- | usage0405    = {{pad|1em}}0.809\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 0.818\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 0.870\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 1.090\n| usage0809    = {{decrease}} 1.076\n| usage0910    = {{decrease}} 1.023\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 1.065\n| usage1112    = {{increase}} 1.088\n| usage1213    = {{increase}} 1.105\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 1.160 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 1.189\n| usage1516    = {{decrease}} 1.187\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 1.189\n| usage1718    = {{decrease}} 1.144\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 1.180\n| code         = ESH\n| dft_category = C2\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.38|-0.3526|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| owner        =\n| gridref      = TQ146658\n| original     = [[London and Southampton Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[London and South Western Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]]\n| years        = {{start date|1838|05|21|df=y}}\n| events       = Opened as ''Ditton Marsh''\n| years1       = {{circa|1840}}\n| events1      = Renamed ''Esher and Hampton Court''\n| years2       = July 1844\n| events2      = Renamed ''Esher and Claremont''\n| years3       = 1 June 1913\n| events3      = Renamed ''Esher''\n}}\n'''Esher railway station''' is a mid-priority station on the [[South Western Main Line]] operated by [[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]] in [[England]].  The station adjoins the north of [[Esher]] with two footpaths skirting [[Sandown Park Racecourse]], the town\u2019s commercial area being 300 metres beyond the racecourse entrance. The station is situated between {{rws|Surbiton}} and {{rws|Hersham}} and is {{convert|14|mi|31|chain|km}} from {{stn|London Waterloo}}.\n\n==History==\nThe railway arrived here in 1838. A minor request stop was immediately opened and a station built and named ''Ditton Marsh,'' being the wetter part of Ditton [[common land|Common]]. The common marks the boundary between what was then the west of [[Thames Ditton]] and [[Esher]]. The station was opened on 21 May 1838, and the name changed to ''Esher and Hampton Court'' about 1840.<ref>{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page=80 |ref=harv }}</ref> It has since been renamed twice more: to ''Esher and Claremont''{{#tag:ref|The reference from 1844 until 1913 was to Prince Leopold's [[Claremont House]] and [[Claremont Landscape Garden|Landscape Garden]] being {{convert|1.5|mi}} south|group= n}} in July 1844, and to ''Esher'' on 1 June 1913.<ref name=Butt92>{{harvnb|Butt|1995|p=92}}</ref> It has also been shown as ''Esher for Claremont'', or as ''Esher for Sandown Park'' in some timetables.<ref name=Butt92 />\n\n==Amenities==\nThe station and track is elevated above street level<ref name=osl>[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/mapsearch.aspx OS Map with Listed Buildings and Parks marked] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424060625/http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/mapsearch.aspx |date=24 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA special gate on the platform opens directly onto Sandown Park racecourse.\n\n==Services==\nAt off-peak times two trains per hour in both directions call at Esher, the termini being [[London Waterloo station]] and the larger [[Surrey]] town of [[Woking]].\n\nAdditional trains operate during peak hours, of which at least 4 (2 in the morning rush-hour, 2 in the evening) terminate at [[Guildford railway station|Guildford]] (which also serves as the terminus for stopping trains on Sundays).<ref>[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk Association of Train Operating Companies - official timetable]</ref>\n\nWoking is the point of change for services to longer distance destinations to the south-west (see stations below).\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line|previous=[[Surbiton railway station|Surbiton]]|route=[[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]]<br /><small>[[South Western Main Line#Services|Waterloo to Woking]]</small>|next=[[Hersham railway station|Hersham]] |col={{SWR colour}} }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n===Former amenities===\nTwo additional [[island platforms]] are disused and not accessible to passengers though passed by through trains.\n\nBus services 515 and on Sundays 715 serve the station.\n\n==Location==\nThe station is to the west of [[Weston Green]] which falls within the [[Esher]] [[post town|postal district.]] Esher parish is close by the station and has included the Sandown Park grounds since its establishment in the early medieval period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43005 |title=Parishes: Esher |author=H.E. Malden (editor) |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |date=1911 |work=A History of the County of Surrey: Volume 3 |accessdate=11 January 2014 }}</ref><ref>H.E. Malden (editor) (1911) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43003 Index Map] Retrieved 11 January 2014 (and see http://www.achurchnearyou.com/esher-christ-church/ for Esher parish map which confirms this unusual slight misnomer)</ref><ref>[http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parishfinder.php?weston+green Weston Green village boundaries] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111183707/http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parishfinder.php?weston+green |date=11 January 2014 }} The [[Church of England]] [[parish]] map.  Retrieved 2014-01-11</ref> A footpath to the west of the station skirts [[Sandown Park Racecourse]] and leads to [[Lower Green Esher]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lowergreenesher.co.uk/2019/11/22/lower-green-map/|title=Modern map of Lower Green Esher|date=2019-11-22|website=Lower Green Esher|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>. The town\u2019s commercial area lies 300 metres beyond the racecourse entrance, followed by [[West End, Esher|West End]] and [[Claremont (country house)|Claremont]]. The station is the closest to Esher by road.<ref name=\"osl\" /> [[Thames Ditton railway station]] on the branch line to [[Hampton Court Palace|Hampton Court]] is closest to the eastern half of [[Weston Green]], which lies within the [[Thames Ditton]] postal district.\n\n==In film, television, fiction and the media==\nEsher railway station featured on an episode of the children\u2019s TV series [[Little Howard's Big Question]], in which the Dutch graphic and mathematical artist [[M. C. Escher]] was confused with Esher and one of his drawings mistakenly thought to be the railway station.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Surrey|Trains}}\n* [[Esher]]\n* [[Weston Green]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n;Notes \n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Esher railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|ESH|KT108DY}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{Elmbridge}}\n{{SWT Stations|Woking=y|IL None=y|Main line None=y|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Former London and South Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1838]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by South Western Railway]]\n[[Category:Borough of Elmbridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Esher station|the request stop in Ontario|Esher station (Ontario)}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name         = Esher\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = Esher station westbound look east2.JPG\n| manager      = [[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]]\n| locale       = [[Esher]]\n| borough      = [[Borough of Elmbridge|Elmbridge]]\n| start        = 21 May 1838\n| platforms    = 4 (2 in use)\n<!-- | usage0405    = {{pad|1em}}0.809\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 0.818\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 0.870\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 1.090\n| usage0809    = {{decrease}} 1.076\n| usage0910    = {{decrease}} 1.023\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 1.065\n| usage1112    = {{increase}} 1.088\n| usage1213    = {{increase}} 1.105\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 1.160 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 1.189\n| usage1516    = {{decrease}} 1.187\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 1.189\n| usage1718    = {{decrease}} 1.144\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 1.180\n| code         = ESH\n| dft_category = C2\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.38|-0.3526|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| owner        =\n| gridref      = TQ146658\n| original     = [[London and Southampton Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[London and South Western Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]]\n| years        = {{start date|1838|05|21|df=y}}\n| events       = Opened as ''Ditton Marsh''\n| years1       = {{circa|1840}}\n| events1      = Renamed ''Esher and Hampton Court''\n| years2       = July 1844\n| events2      = Renamed ''Esher and Claremont''\n| years3       = 1 June 1913\n| events3      = Renamed ''Esher''\n}}\n'''Esher railway station''' is a mid-priority station on the [[South Western Main Line]] operated by [[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]] in [[England]].  The station adjoins the north of [[Esher]] with two footpaths skirting [[Sandown Park Racecourse]], the town\u2019s commercial area being 300 metres beyond the racecourse entrance. The station is situated between {{rws|Surbiton}} and {{rws|Hersham}} and is {{convert|14|mi|31|chain|km}} from {{stn|London Waterloo}}.\n\n==History==\nThe railway arrived here in 1838. A minor request stop was immediately opened and a station built and named ''Ditton Marsh,'' being the wetter part of Ditton [[common land|Common]]. The common marks the boundary between what was then the west of [[Thames Ditton]] and [[Esher]]. The station was opened on 21 May 1838, and the name changed to ''Esher and Hampton Court'' about 1840.<ref>{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page=80 |ref=harv }}</ref> It has since been renamed twice more: to ''Esher and Claremont''{{#tag:ref|The reference from 1844 until 1913 was to Prince Leopold's [[Claremont House]] and [[Claremont Landscape Garden|Landscape Garden]] being {{convert|1.5|mi}} south|group= n}} in July 1844, and to ''Esher'' on 1 June 1913.<ref name=Butt92>{{harvnb|Butt|1995|p=92}}</ref> It has also been shown as ''Esher for Claremont'', or as ''Esher for Sandown Park'' in some timetables.<ref name=Butt92 />\n\n==Amenities==\nThe station and track is elevated above street level<ref name=osl>[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/mapsearch.aspx OS Map with Listed Buildings and Parks marked] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424060625/http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/mapsearch.aspx |date=24 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA special gate on the platform opens directly onto Sandown Park racecourse.\n\n==Services==\nAt off-peak times two trains per hour in both directions call at Esher, the termini being [[London Waterloo station]] and the larger [[Surrey]] town of [[Woking]].\n\nAdditional trains operate during peak hours, of which at least 4 (2 in the morning rush-hour, 2 in the evening) terminate at [[Guildford railway station|Guildford]] (which also serves as the terminus for stopping trains on Sundays).<ref>[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk Association of Train Operating Companies - official timetable]</ref>\n\nWoking is the point of change for services to longer distance destinations to the south-west (see stations below).\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line|previous=[[Surbiton railway station|Surbiton]]|route=[[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]]<br /><small>[[South Western Main Line#Services|Waterloo to Woking]]</small>|next=[[Hersham railway station|Hersham]] |col={{SWR colour}} }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n===Former amenities===\nTwo additional [[island platforms]] are disused and not accessible to passengers though passed by through trains.\n\nBus services 515 and on Sundays 715 serve the station.\n\n==Location==\nThe station is to the west of [[Weston Green]] which falls within the [[Esher]] [[post town|postal district.]] Esher parish is close by the station and has included the Sandown Park grounds since its establishment in the early medieval period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43005 |title=Parishes: Esher |author=H.E. Malden (editor) |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |date=1911 |work=A History of the County of Surrey: Volume 3 |accessdate=11 January 2014 }}</ref><ref>H.E. Malden (editor) (1911) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43003 Index Map] Retrieved 11 January 2014 (and see http://www.achurchnearyou.com/esher-christ-church/ for Esher parish map which confirms this unusual slight misnomer)</ref><ref>[http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parishfinder.php?weston+green Weston Green village boundaries] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111183707/http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parishfinder.php?weston+green |date=11 January 2014 }} The [[Church of England]] [[parish]] map.  Retrieved 2014-01-11</ref> A footpath to the west of the station skirts [[Sandown Park Racecourse]] and leads to Lower Green Esher<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lowergreenesher.co.uk/2019/11/22/lower-green-map/|title=Modern map of Lower Green Esher|date=2019-11-22|website=Lower Green Esher|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>. The town\u2019s commercial area lies 300 metres beyond the racecourse entrance, followed by [[West End, Esher|West End]] and [[Claremont (country house)|Claremont]]. The station is the closest to Esher by road.<ref name=\"osl\" /> [[Thames Ditton railway station]] on the branch line to [[Hampton Court Palace|Hampton Court]] is closest to the eastern half of [[Weston Green]], which lies within the [[Thames Ditton]] postal district.\n\n==In film, television, fiction and the media==\nEsher railway station featured on an episode of the children\u2019s TV series [[Little Howard's Big Question]], in which the Dutch graphic and mathematical artist [[M. C. Escher]] was confused with Esher and one of his drawings mistakenly thought to be the railway station.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Surrey|Trains}}\n* [[Esher]]\n* [[Weston Green]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n;Notes \n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Esher railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|ESH|KT108DY}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{Elmbridge}}\n{{SWT Stations|Woking=y|IL None=y|Main line None=y|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Former London and South Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1838]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by South Western Railway]]\n[[Category:Borough of Elmbridge]]\n", "name_user": "AM-LowerGreenEsher", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLocation:added a link to a page about Lower Green", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esher_railway_station"}
